ative and legal decisions which initiated and concluded this calamity. Finally, the authors analyze the principal constitutional issues involved in the evacuation and their implications for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral. 4aSocial Science. 4aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBarnhart, Edward N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnhart, Edward N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatson, Floyd W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatson, Floyd W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 atenBroek, Jacobus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 atenBroek, Jacobus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035313840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520353138423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520353138/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles